Planner, David Fields. And so I may be leaning on some of them for

01:25.912 --> 01:29.480
some of your questions. Let me go ahead and start.

01:29.850 --> 01:33.266
So my name is Margaret Wallace Brown. I'm the director of the Planning and Development

01:33.298 --> 01:36.406
Department. And before I present an overview of the

01:36.428 --> 01:39.998
Planning and Development Department budget, I'd like to take a moment to reaffirm

01:40.114 --> 01:43.466
my deep appreciation for your support of the planning team and all the

01:43.488 --> 01:46.774
work we do. We take great pride in being a resource

01:46.822 --> 01:50.038
for the Mayor and Council districts and our fellow departments.

01:50.134 --> 01:54.750
We take our work very seriously when we work with you. In 2021,

01:54.820 --> 01:58.266
we adopted a new mission statement growing and Preserving

01:58.298 --> 02:02.334
Houston's Diverse Communities to create a resilient city with

02:02.372 --> 02:05.826
record number of platts and permits and an increasing portfolio of

02:05.848 --> 02:09.874
new projects. 2021 has been our most productive year and

02:09.912 --> 02:13.406
our most innovative year. I'd like to demonstrate how we are fulfilling

02:13.438 --> 02:17.270
that mission as I share a few highlight reels of our accomplishments.

02:17.770 --> 02:21.654
First of all, our platting requests hit an all time high with

02:21.692 --> 02:26.358
over more than 3000 platts in 2021. That was a 25%

02:26.444 --> 02:30.060
increase on our previous record year, which was 2020.

02:30.430 --> 02:34.170
We also saw a steady increase in building permits, with 22

02:34.320 --> 02:38.714
300 building permits planners reviewing approximately 1200

02:38.752 --> 02:42.122
plans per month. On a different

02:42.176 --> 02:46.186
note, Friedmanstown was designated as the city's first heritage district.

02:46.298 --> 02:49.962
We also added ten more landmarks, a new historic district,

02:50.026 --> 02:53.506
and we have another one in the works. Our team is engaging with residents in

02:53.528 --> 02:57.170
Glenburg Valley, where we conducted a window workshop and worked on design

02:57.240 --> 02:59.570
guidelines for three historic districts.

03:00.470 --> 03:04.018
More accomplishments include our transportation planning area,

03:04.104 --> 03:07.206
which our Vision Zero Action plan earned a

03:07.228 --> 03:10.466
Gold Award for implementation from the Texas Chapter of the American Planning

03:10.498 --> 03:14.178
Association. Vision Zero is implementing all 13

03:14.274 --> 03:17.894
priority actions, and highlights include continuing engagement

03:17.942 --> 03:22.150
to identify locations of concern updating the city street designs,

03:22.230 --> 03:25.926
redesigning ten high injury network locations, and receiving

03:25.958 --> 03:30.010
$4 million in highway safety improvement funding from Techstot.

03:30.690 --> 03:34.254
The first more space Main Street patio opened with Little

03:34.292 --> 03:37.578
Dipper. Followed shortly after that with Shay McElroy, the Flying

03:37.594 --> 03:41.466
Saucer and Finn Hall. The More space Main Street initiative

03:41.498 --> 03:44.574
was a great success and was approved for an extension,

03:44.622 --> 03:48.354
keeping it going through 2023 in 2021,

03:48.392 --> 03:51.806
together with our partners, we completed the Austin Hutchins,

03:51.918 --> 03:56.370
Gray, Leland and Polk Street Bikeways,

03:56.450 --> 03:59.746
including Cullen Boulevard. Also, they were initiated

03:59.778 --> 04:03.538
in response to the Build 50 challenge. We added the Clear Lake West

04:03.554 --> 04:07.026
Chase Trail extensions and segments of the Spring Branch Trail.

04:07.138 --> 04:10.726
So now we have High comfort bikeway off of East Freeway

04:10.758 --> 04:14.742
at Federal and Maxi and these complete 40 miles

04:14.806 --> 04:18.140
of high comfort bike network in our city.

04:18.510 --> 04:22.154
The transportation team also engaged with the community to build safety improvements

04:22.202 --> 04:25.578
in Briar Meadows and set a guest with council

04:25.594 --> 04:28.986
members Thomas and Jackson. We partnered with Harris

04:29.018 --> 04:32.306
County Health Department, received funding from MD Anderson to start the

04:32.328 --> 04:35.826
city's first Safe Routes to School program in

04:35.848 --> 04:39.854
Acres Home. Our Livable Places Action Committee celebrated

04:39.902 --> 04:43.886
its first anniversary, reached consensus on recommendations from Chapter

04:43.918 --> 04:47.442
42 technical amendments, which you graciously approved yesterday,

04:47.586 --> 04:51.106
established a focus group to work on conservation districts, and released

04:51.138 --> 04:54.214
a single family residential survey that garnered over 1200

04:54.252 --> 04:57.930
responses. We received a grant from the AARP,

04:58.350 --> 05:01.990
which we used to organize an accessory dwelling unit

05:02.070 --> 05:05.782
garage apartment for many design competition to promote

05:05.846 --> 05:09.238
compact, affordable housing design options for Houstonians.

05:09.334 --> 05:12.894
The grant funded a series of workshops and the design contest and

05:12.932 --> 05:16.634
culminated in the publication of a book, all of which was managed,

05:16.682 --> 05:20.918
implemented and designed by our staff in the complete communities

05:21.034 --> 05:24.642
planning and development led initiatives such as Neighborhood Character preservation Tool

05:24.696 --> 05:28.578
Workshops, Lights on Houston Community Events Building

05:28.744 --> 05:32.670
Food Security Workshop and working with CenterPoint Energy Agency's

05:32.750 --> 05:36.306
Action Program. So these are our accomplishments over

05:36.328 --> 05:39.574
the past year, but I also want to provide a very brief overview of our

05:39.612 --> 05:43.126
priorities, new projects and frequently recurring quests that we're expecting to

05:43.148 --> 05:46.786
come for the coming year. As all of you know, we're working with council districts

05:46.818 --> 05:50.458
